summary:
The Security Council adopted Resolution 1302 (2000) on June 8, 2000, recalling previous relevant resolutions, particularly those related to Iraq. The Council aims to address the humanitarian needs of the Iraqi people until the Government of Iraq fulfills relevant resolutions, notably Resolution 687 (1991).

The resolution decides to extend the provisions of Resolution 986 (1995) for 180 days, starting June 9, 2000, with some exceptions. It prioritizes the allocation of funds for food, nutrition, and health sectors, with 13% of the sum produced used for specific purposes.

The Secretary-General is requested to ensure effective implementation, enhance the UN observation process in Iraq, and report to the Council 90 days after the resolution's entry into force and prior to the 180-day period's end. The Council will review the resolution's implementation and consider renewal if satisfactory.

The Committee established by Resolution 661 (1990) and the Secretary-General are tasked with reporting on implementation and approving lists of basic water and sanitation supplies. The resolution allows for the use of up to $600 million from the escrow account for reasonable expenses.
The Security Council:

Recalls previous resolutions and expresses intention to consider favourably renewal of measures;

Decides to use funds in escrow account for purposes outlined in resolution 986 (1995) and maintains paragraph 20 of resolution 1284 (1999) in force;

Welcomes Committee's efforts to review applications expeditiously and encourages further efforts;

Calls on Iraq to implement paragraph 27 of resolution 1284 (1999) and requests Secretary-General to review and report on implementation;

Requests Secretary-General to submit recommendations on minimizing delay in payment of petroleum sales and utilization of excess funds;

Urges States to cooperate in implementation of resolution and facilitate transit of humanitarian supplies;

Appeals to States to continue cooperating in submission of applications and issue of export licences;

Stresses need to ensure respect for security and safety of persons involved in implementation;

Invites Secretary-General to appoint experts to prepare comprehensive report on humanitarian situation in Iraq by 26 November 2000;

Decides to remain seized of the matter.
